div.p:
The unit vectors in this system (blue vectors in the
        figures), expressed in Cartesian coordinates, are r̂=(cos⁡θcos⁡ζcos⁡θsin⁡ζsin⁡θ),θ̂=(−sin⁡θcos⁡ζ−sin⁡θsin⁡ζcos⁡θ),ζ̂=(−sin⁡ζcos⁡ζ0)\hat{r}=
        \left(
            \begin{array}{c}
            \cos\theta \cos \zeta \\
            \cos \theta \sin \zeta \\
            \sin \theta \\
            \end{array}
        \right),\;
        \hat{\theta}=
        \left(
            \begin{array}{c}
            -\sin\theta\cos\zeta \\
            -\sin\theta\sin\zeta \\
            \cos\theta \\
            \end{array}
        \right),\;
        \hat{\zeta}=
        \left(
            \begin{array}{c}
            -\sin\zeta \\
            \cos\zeta \\
            0 \\
            \end{array}
        \right)

Therefore, to translate a field vector with base (rr, θ\theta, ζ\zeta) and components (aa, bb, cc) to Cartesian coordinates, the base
        can be found using the translation above, and the vector using
        the scaled unit vectors: 𝐩=ar̂+bθ̂+cζ̂𝐩=(acos⁡θcos⁡ζ−bsin⁡θcos⁡ζ−csin⁡ζ)x̂+(acos⁡θsin⁡ζ−bsin⁡θsin⁡ζ+ccos⁡ζ)ŷ+(asin⁡θ+bcos⁡θ)ẑ\begin{aligned}
        \mathbf{p}&=a\hat{r}+b\hat{\theta}+c\hat{\zeta}\\
        \mathbf{p}&=(a\cos\theta\cos\zeta-b\sin\theta\cos\zeta-c\sin\zeta)\hat{x}\\
        &+(a\cos\theta\sin\zeta-b\sin\theta\sin\zeta+c\cos\zeta)\hat{y}\\
        &+(a\sin\theta+b\cos\theta)\hat{z}
        \end{aligned}

The simplest field to imagine is a torus with constant
        magnitude in the ζ̂\hat{\zeta}
        (toroidal) direction. 𝐁(r,θ,ζ)={1ζ̂if r<r00otherwise\begin{aligned}
        \textbf{B}(r, \theta, \zeta)=\begin{cases}
        1\hat{\zeta} & \text{if } r < r_0 \\
        0 & \text{otherwise}
        \end{cases}
        \end{aligned}

Accounting for this fact leads us to the field: 𝐁(r,θ,ζ)={R0/(R0+rcos⁡θ)ζ̂if r<r00otherwise\begin{aligned}
        \textbf{B}(r, \theta, \zeta)=\begin{cases}
        R_0/(R_0 + r\cos\theta)\hat{\zeta} & \text{if } r < r_0
        \\
        0 & \text{otherwise}
        \end{cases}
        \end{aligned} Since R=R0+rcos⁡θR=R_0+r\cos\theta. Choosing a
        numerator of R0R_0 normalizes
        this so that the field along the central circle 11.

At the stating time, v∥=vy=v⟂=vxv_\parallel=v_y=v_\perp=v_x. Since
        v∥2+v⟂2=v2v_\parallel^2+v_\perp^2=v^2, we
        have that v⟂2=v∥2=v2/2v_\perp^2=v_\parallel^2=v^2/2, so the
        drift velocity should be roughly 𝐯drift=𝐯∇B+𝐯R=(mv⟂22qR0+mv∥2qR0)ẑ𝐯drift=(mv24qR0+mv22qR0)ẑ=(3mv24qR0)ẑ𝐯drift=189ẑ m/s=0.00086ẑ\begin{aligned}
        &\textbf{v}_{drift}=\textbf{v}_{\nabla B} +
        \textbf{v}_R=\left(\frac{mv_\perp^2}{2qR_0}+\frac{mv_\parallel^2}{qR_0}\right)\hat{z}\\
        &\textbf{v}_{drift}=\left(\frac{mv^2}{4qR_0}+\frac{mv^2}{2qR_0}\right)\hat{z}=\left(\frac{3mv^2}{4qR_0}\right)\hat{z}\\
        &\textbf{v}_{drift}=189\hat{z}\textrm{ m/s}=0.00086\hat{z}
        \end{aligned}
